## Naming Conventions

### File Names

- **Permanent Notes**: `Declarative-Title.md`
- **Literature Notes**: `LIT-Source-Title.md`
- **Fleeting Notes**: `FLEET-Brief-Title.md`
- **Study Plans**: `[Context-Name]-Study-Plan.md`
- **Context Folders**: `[Context-Name]` (PascalCase, no spaces)
- **Index Files**: `Master-Index.md`, `Context-Map.md`

### Note Titles

- Must be declarative statements
- Express a complete idea
- Example: "HTTP-methods-define-request-semantics" not "HTTP Methods"

## Tagging Standards

### Format

All tags must follow: `#CONTEXT-REFERENCE`

### Rules

- Use PascalCase for both Context and Reference
- Context represents the domain or area of study
- Reference represents the specific concept or topic
- Multiple tags per note are mandatory for cross-referencing

### Examples

```markdown
#AWS-EventDriven
#Architecture-Microservices
#Python-AsyncIO
#DataStructures-BinaryTrees
#Security-OAuth2
#Frontend-ReactHooks
```

### Tag Application

- Minimum 3 tags per permanent note
- Tags must connect to other contexts when applicable
- Tags must support Graph View navigation

## Linking Standards

### Internal Links

- Use WikiLinks format: `[[Note-Title]]`
- Link to prerequisite concepts at note beginning
- Link to related concepts at note end
- Embed diagrams using: `![[diagram-name]]`

### Link Structure in Permanent Notes

```markdown
# Note Title

**Prerequisites**: [[prerequisite-note-1]] [[prerequisite-note-2]]

[Note content]

**Related**: [[related-note-1]] [[related-note-2]]
**Tags**: #Context-Reference #Context-Reference #Context-Reference
```

## Diagram Standards

### Syntax

All diagrams must use Mermaid syntax exclusively.

### Diagram Types by Purpose

- **Concept Dependencies**: flowchart
- **Study Plan Sequences**: flowchart or timeline
- **Knowledge Graphs**: graph
- **Mind Maps**: mindmap
- **Class Relationships**: classDiagram

### Example: Study Plan Sequence

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    A[HTTP-methods-define-request-semantics] --> B[REST-constraints-define-architectural-style]
    A --> C[HTTP-status-codes-communicate-response-state]
    B --> D[REST-APIs-use-HTTP-methods-for-CRUD]
    C --> D
    D --> E[API-versioning-maintains-backward-compatibility]
    
    style A fill:#e1f5ff
    style B fill:#e1f5ff
    style C fill:#e1f5ff
    style D fill:#fff4e1
    style E fill:#ffe1e1
```

### Example: Context Dependency Graph

```mermaid
graph LR
    A[#Backend-APIs] --> B[#Architecture-Microservices]
    A --> C[#Security-Authentication]
    B --> D[#Infrastructure-Containers]
    C --> E[#Security-OAuth2]
    D --> F[#DevOps-Orchestration]
```

## Zettelkasten Compliance

### Atomic Concept Decomposition

Each permanent note must:
- Address exactly one atomic concept
- Be explainable in 200-300 words
- Have a declarative title expressing the complete idea
- Stand alone without requiring other notes to be understood

### Note Structure Template

```markdown
# [Declarative-Note-Title]

**Prerequisites**: [[prerequisite-1]] [[prerequisite-2]]

## Concept

[200-300 word explanation of the atomic concept]

## Example

[Concrete example demonstrating the concept]

## Related

[[related-concept-1]]
[[related-concept-2]]

**Tags**: #Context-Reference #Context-Reference #Context-Reference
```

### Dependency Mapping

Every permanent note must declare:
- Prerequisite concepts (what must be understood first)
- Related concepts (what connects laterally)
- Context tags (where this fits in the knowledge graph)

